SIMPLE: moan
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Moan
<hw>Moan</hw> <pr>(m⟦omac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Moaned</conjf> <pr>(m⟦omac⟧nd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Moaning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>m⟦aemac⟧nan</ets> to moan, also, to mean; but in the latter sense
perh. a different word. Cf. <er>Mean</er> to intend.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To make a low prolonged sound of grief or pain, whether articulate
or not; to groan softly and continuously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unpitied and unheard, where misery <qex>moans</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let there bechance him pitiful mischances,⟦br⟧
To make him <qex>moan</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To emit a sound like moan; -- said of things
inanimate; <as>as, the wind <ex>moans</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moan</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Moan
<hw>Moan</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bewail audibly; to
lament.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye floods, ye woods, ye echoes, <qex>moan</qex>⟦br⟧
My dear Columbo, dead and gone.</q> <rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To afflict; to distress.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which infinitely <qex>moans</qex> me.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. &
Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moan</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Moan
<hw>Moan</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mone</ets>. See
<er>Moan</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A low prolonged
sound, articulate or not, indicative of pain or of grief; a low
groan.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sullen <qex>moans</qex>, hollow groans.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A low mournful or murmuring sound; -- of
things.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rippling waters made a pleasant <qex>moan</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moanful</ent>⟦br⟧
